{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640948"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17847"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.04,0,0.04,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78247"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10561"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63656"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26833"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78247"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInsulin is released in response to a meal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Occurs in two phases","Occurs irrespective of glucose kinetics","Does not involve interactions with secretagogues","Is independent of incretin hormones","Is solely dependent on blood glucose levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPhysiological insulin release in response to a meal occurs in \u003Cstrong\u003Etwo phases\u003C/strong\u003E. The first phase is a rapid release of pre-stored insulin from the pancreas, which occurs within minutes of glucose entering the bloodstream. This is followed by a second, slower phase of insulin release, which involves the synthesis and secretion of new insulin molecules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInsulin release is not independent of glucose kinetics; it is closely tied to blood glucose levels. As glucose levels rise, insulin secretion increases to facilitate glucose uptake by cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInteractions with \u003Cstrong\u003Esecretagogues\u003C/strong\u003E, such as incretin hormones, are crucial in the regulation of insulin release. Incretins, like glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1), enhance insulin secretion in response to meals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile blood glucose levels are a primary driver of insulin release, the process is not \u003Cstrong\u003Esolely dependent\u003C/strong\u003E on them. Other factors, including neural inputs and hormonal signals, also play a role.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Physiological insulin release in response to a meal occurs in two phases: an initial rapid release followed by a slower, sustained release.","Insulin release is influenced by glucose levels and other factors such as incretin hormones.","Secretagogues, substances that promote insulin secretion, play a role in the regulation of insulin release."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568. PMID: 33397651; PMCID: PMC7778149"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63656"}},"question"